<chapter subject="Physics" id="106" name="Electromagnetic Waves">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Who predicted the existence of electromagnetic waves based on theoretical grounds?</text>
            <option id="A">Maxwell</option><option id="B">Hertz</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Maxwell's equations unified electricity and magnetism.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Who experimentally confirmed the existence of electromagnetic waves?</text>
            <option id="A">Hertz</option><option id="B">Maxwell</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Produced waves in the laboratory using spark gap oscillator.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Electromagnetic waves are produced by ____ charges.</text>
            <option id="A">Accelerated</option><option id="B">Stationary</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Time-varying currents or accelerating charges.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The speed of electromagnetic waves in vacuum is c = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3 x 10^8 m/s</option><option id="B">3 x 10^6 m/s</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fundamental constant of nature.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The propagation of EM waves is perpendicular to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Both E and B fields</option><option id="B">E field only</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Transverse nature of EM waves.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The ratio of magnitude of electric field E to magnetic field B in an EM wave is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">c (speed of light)</option><option id="B">1/c</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>E₀ / B₀ = c.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following has the shortest wavelength in the EM spectrum?</text>
            <option id="A">Gamma rays</option><option id="B">Radio waves</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highest frequency and energy.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following has the longest wavelength in the EM spectrum?</text>
            <option id="A">Radio waves</option><option id="B">X-rays</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lowest frequency and energy.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The part of the EM spectrum used in RADAR is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Microwaves</option><option id="B">Ultraviolet</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Suitable for detection due to shorter wavelength than radio.</explanation>
        </explanation>
        <question>
            <text>Which waves are used for telecommunication (Cell phones)?</text>
            <option id="A">Radio waves / Microwaves</option><option id="B">Infrared</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Can travel long distances and penetrate obstacles.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The waves used in household remote controls are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Infrared</option><option id="B">Visible light</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Low frequency, non-ionizing waves.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Greenhouse effect is primarily due to ____ radiation.</text>
            <option id="A">Infrared (Heat)</option><option id="B">Ultraviolet</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Trapped by atmospheric gases.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Radiation used for water purification is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ultraviolet (UV)</option><option id="B">X-rays</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Kills bacteria by damaging DNA.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which rays are used to study crystal structure?</text>
            <option id="A">X-rays</option><option id="B">Gamma rays</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Wavelength comparable to atomic spacing.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ozone layer in the atmosphere blocks ____ radiation from the sun.</text>
            <option id="A">Ultraviolet (UV)</option><option id="B">Infrared</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Protects biological life from harmful effects.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Electromagnetic waves carry ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Energy, Momentum</option><option id="B">Charge, Mass</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>They exert radiation pressure.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Radiation pressure of an EM wave is P = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">I / c</option><option id="B">I * c</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Where I is intensity and c is speed of light.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The value of c is given by c = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1 / √(μ₀ε₀)</option><option id="B">√(μ₀ε₀)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Links electromagnetic constants to light speed.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Do EM waves require a medium for propagation?</text>
            <option id="A">No</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>They travel through vacuum.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In an EM wave, energy is distributed ____ between E and B fields.</text>
            <option id="A">Equally</option><option id="B">Unequally</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>u_E = u_B = 1/2 ε₀ E^2 = B^2 / 2μ₀.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Displacement current density J_d is J_d = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">ε₀ (dE / dt)</option><option id="B">dΦ / dt</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Arises from time-varying electric flux.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The wavelength range of visible light is approx ____.</text>
            <option id="A">400nm to 700nm</option><option id="B">1nm to 100nm</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Violet to Red.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which EM waves travel at the highest speed in vacuum?</text>
            <option id="A">All travel at same speed (c)</option><option id="B">Gamma rays</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Universal speed for all frequencies in vacuum.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The amplitude of magnetic field B₀ related to E₀ is B₀ = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">E₀ / c</option><option id="B">E₀ * c</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard wave relation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The intensity of an EM wave depends on ____ of the field.</text>
            <option id="A">Square of amplitude</option><option id="B">Amplitude</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>I ∝ E₀^2.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Infrared waves are also called ____ waves.</text>
            <option id="A">Heat</option><option id="B">Light</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Emitted by hot bodies.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following has the lowest frequency?</text>
            <option id="A">Radio waves</option><option id="B">Visible light</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Longest wavelength implies lowest frequency.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Maximum frequency in the EM spectrum belongs to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Gamma rays</option><option id="B">Microwaves</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Most energetic radiation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Can EM waves be polarized?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (Transverse nature)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard property of all transverse waves.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The physical significance of displacement current is that it produces ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Magnetic field</option><option id="B">Electric field only</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Completes the circuit in gaps like capacitors.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit of displacement current is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ampere (A)</option><option id="B">Volt</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>It is a type of current.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Maxwell's equations describe the behavior of ____ fields.</text>
            <option id="A">Electric and Magnetic</option><option id="B">Gravitational</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>The laws of electromagnetism.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The average intensity of a wave I = (1/2)ε₀ c E₀^2. This I is the ____ through unit area.</text>
            <option id="A">Power</option><option id="B">Energy</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unit W/m^2.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Welders wear dark goggles to protect eyes from ____ radiation.</text>
            <option id="A">Ultraviolet (UV)</option><option id="B">Infrared</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>High energy UV produced during welding.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Does the speed of EM waves change in a medium?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (v = c / n)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Depends on refractive index n.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The frequency of an EM wave ____ when it enters a medium.</text>
            <option id="A">Remains same</option><option id="B">Changes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Frequency is a property of the source.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The wavelength of an EM wave ____ when it enters a medium.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreases</option><option id="B">Increases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>λ' = λ / n since v = f λ.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Poynting vector S represents ____ of EM wave.</text>
            <option id="A">Energy flux density</option><option id="B">Momentum</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>S = (1/μ₀) E × B.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Maxwell modified ____ law to include displacement current.</text>
            <option id="A">Ampere's Circuital</option><option id="B">Faraday's</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Resulting in Ampere-Maxwell Law.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Does an EM wave exert pressure on a surface?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (Radiation pressure)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to transfer of momentum.</explanation>
        </question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Relationship between E₀, B₀ and c: c = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">E₀ / B₀</option><option id="B">B₀ / E₀</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ratio of amplitudes of electric and magnetic fields.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Wave number k of an EM wave is related to wavelength λ by k = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2π / λ</option><option id="B">λ / 2π</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Spatial frequency of the wave.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The instantaneous energy density of electric field is u_E = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1/2 ε₀ E^2</option><option id="B">ε₀ E^2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy per unit volume in ε vac.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The instantaneous energy density of magnetic field is u_B = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">B^2 / 2μ₀</option><option id="B">μ₀ B^2 / 2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Magnetic energy storage density.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The average electric energy density of EM wave is u_E_avg = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1/4 ε₀ E₀^2</option><option id="B">1/2 ε₀ E₀^2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Average of sin^2 over a cycle is 1/2.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which part of EM spectrum is produced by inner shell electrons in heavy atoms?</text>
            <option id="A">X-rays</option><option id="B">Ultraviolet</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Transitions to lowest energy levels release high energy photons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Source of energy in Gamma rays is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nuclear transitions</option><option id="B">Atomic electron levels</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Radioactive decay of nuclei.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Electromagnetic waves carry momentum p = ____ for energy U.</text>
            <option id="A">U / c</option><option id="B">U * c</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Basic relationship in relativity for massless waves.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Radiation from a hot body follow ____ law.</text>
            <option id="A">Stefan-Boltzmann</option><option id="B">Newton's cooling only</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Total energy ∝ T^4.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which EM waves are used in thermal imaging cameras?</text>
            <option id="A">Infrared</option><option id="B">Visible</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Detect heat radiation emitted by objects.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Displacement current Id between plates of C = 1μF for dV/dt = 10^6 V/s is ____ A.</text>
            <option id="A">1</option><option id="B">0.1</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Id = C (dV/dt) = 1e-6 * 1e6 = 1 A.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Relation between E₀ and I in vacuum is I = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1/2 ε₀ c E₀^2</option><option id="B">ε₀ c E₀^2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Average power per unit area.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The amplitude of magnetic field for E₀ = 300 V/m is B₀ = ____ T.</text>
            <option id="A">10^-6</option><option id="B">10^-4</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>B₀ = E₀ / c = 300 / 3e8 = 10^-6 T.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>EM waves of frequencies 30 MHz to 300 MHz are used for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">VHF (TV, FM radio)</option><option id="B">AM radio</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Very High Frequency band.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In free space, magnetic field wave is B = B₀sin(kx - ωt)j. Electric field wave is E = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">c B₀sin(kx - ωt)k</option><option id="B">c B₀sin(kx - ωt)i</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Directions must be mutually perpendicular (x, y, z).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The ratio of average energy densities u_E / u_B is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1</option><option id="B">c</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy is shared equally.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following describes the behavior of displacement current?</text>
            <option id="A">It is present wherever electric flux changes</option><option id="B">It is only in wires</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Maxwell's extension for time-varying fields.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Displacement current Id through surface S is given by Id = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">ε₀ (dΦ_E / dt)</option><option id="B">μ₀ (dΦ_B / dt)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Rate of change of electric flux.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In Ampere-Maxwell Law, ∮B.dl = μ₀ (____).</text>
            <option id="A">I + Id</option><option id="B">I - Id</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sum of conduction and displacement currents.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which waves can travel around the Earth by reflecting from Ionosphere?</text>
            <option id="A">Radio waves (Shortwave)</option><option id="B">Microwaves</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sky wave propagation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Do EM waves carry information?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (Modulation)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Base for all wireless communications.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Microwave oven frequency is tuned to match frequency of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Water molecules resonance</option><option id="B">Metal atoms</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dielectric heating of water content.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The speed of EM waves in a medium depends on ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Permittivity, Permeability</option><option id="B">Frequency, Amplitude</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>v = 1 / √(με).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Total energy of photo-electromagnetic radiation is E = n * ____.</text>
            <option id="A">h f</option><option id="B">h / f</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Quantization of EM field (Photons).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Refractive index n is related to ε_r and μ_r by n = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">√(ε_r μ_r)</option><option id="B">ε_r μ_r</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>From Maxwell equations speeds definition.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Radiation pressure for vertical reflection is P = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2I / c</option><option id="B">I / c</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Momentum change is twice (p final - p init).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Visible light is a small part of the total spectrum?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Spans only a few hundred nanometers.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Frequency of photon associated with 300m wavelength radio wave is ____ MHz.</text>
            <option id="A">1</option><option id="B">10</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
